#Text=Creator of website satirizing Glenn Beck on winning domain name case
#Text=Tuesday , November 10 , 2009

#Text=Wikinews interviewed the creator of a parody website satirizing American political commentator Glenn Beck , about his thoughts after prevailing in a domain name dispute brought by Beck before the World Intellectual Property Organization ( WIPO ) in Geneva , Switzerland .
#Text=Florida resident Isaac Eiland-Hall created the website in September , and it asserts Beck uses questionable tactics " to spread lies and misinformation " .
#Text=Eiland-Hall was represented in the case by free speech lawyer Marc Randazza .

#Text=Wikinews interviewed Randazza for the article " US free speech lawyer Marc Randazza discusses Glenn Beck parody " , and previously reported on the Beck v. Eiland-Hall case in articles , " US free speech lawyer defends satire of Glenn Beck " , " Satirical website criticizes Glenn Beck for ' hypocritical ' attempts to silence free speech " , and " Glenn Beck loses domain name case over parody website " .

column1: #Text=Background
#Text=Glenn Beck in 2007 Image : Mark87 .
#Text=Eiland-Hall registered the website at the domain " www.GlennBeckRapedAndMurderedAYoungGirlIn1990.com " .
#Text=Its premise was derived from a joke statement made by Gilbert Gottfried about fellow comedian Bob Saget .
#Text=Users of the Internet discussion community
#Text=Fark first applied the joke to Beck , and it then became popular on several social media sites .
#Text=Eiland-Hall saw the discussion on Fark , and created a website about it .
#Text=The website asserts it does not believe the rumors to be true , commenting , " [ b]ut we think Glenn Beck definitely uses tactics like this to spread lies and misinformation .

#Text=Beck 's lawyers sent letters to the domain name registrar where they referred to the domain name itself as  defamatory " , but failed to get the site removed .

column1: #Text=Beck filed a formal complaint with the Switzerland-based agency of the United Nations , WIPO , who operate under regulations laid out by the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and Numbers .
#Text=Beck asserted the website 's usage is libelous , bad faith , and could confuse potential consumers .
#Text=Beck 's complaint was filed under the process called the Uniform Domain Name Dispute Resolution Policy .
#Text=This policy allows trademark owners to begin an administrative action by complaining that a certain domain registration is in " bad faith " .
#Text=Beck argued the site should be shut down because it is an infringement upon his trademark in his own name , " Glenn Beck " .
#Text=Eiland-Hall retained Randazza as his attorney after receiving threatening letters from legal representatives of Beck .
#Text=On September 28 , Randazza filed a response brief to WIPO , contending the site is " protected political speech " , due to it 's " satirical political humor " .
